metadata.name: Tangentum #15
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: pulau gen #196
metadata.description:
We have spent months looking for the anatomy of space. I think each of us have really been searching for it for decades. But  only recently have we decided to conjugate our efforts. 

The arrangement of the features of a territory has been seen by many before us as something to be probed. The topographic endeavours of the explorers who have sliced the earth tried to make it finite. But even they know that they missed most of what was to be found. 

Daratan has started their explorations with pen and paper. Their pulaus are three-dimensional projections of units extracted from a planet that doesn‚Äôt exist. And yet these representations are immediately naturalised, for they evoke geographic norms which describe the world to those who wouldn‚Äôt see it for what it is. 

Anaglyphic took the opposite perspective, and set up abstraction generators that would enable others to create areas to be explored. The anaverse is a system which generates topographies according to simple rules which, called recursively, allow for unbounded diversity. Rather than observing space and trying to deduce what it is, they allow humans to build space and, in the process, prompt them to reflect on what they think it should be.

The temporary intersection of these individual journeys yielded pulau gen. In an attempt to demineralise both our media, we decided to populate the pulaus with guardian creatures. The whales, octopi and birds are as many reminders that a topographic representation is usually missing the one thing that matters the most about it: the life it can host.

metadata.name: sinuosity #84
metadata.description:
sinuosity is defined as:

- (n.) the ability to curve or bend easily and flexibly.

sinuous is defined as a couple of things:

- (adj.) having many curves and turns.
- (adj.) lithe and supple.

each curve anchors to the center. 

maybe that center is a life. (maybe that center is you.)

maybe that curve is a relationship. (or a job.) (or repressed trauma that needs processing.)

maybe that curve has other curves within. (it probably does.)

sometimes there are many curves at once. (usually this the case.) 

occasionally, there may only be one. (life isn‚Äôt always so complicated.) 

whatever curves the moment contains it can help to step away and see how they come together. (this is not always easy.)

metadata.name: Gemrock #81
metadata.description:
In this work, strands of pearls and colorful stones are arranged together like particles of memory and light, creating overlapping layers of color and texture. The color combinations begin from a delicate opening, where tiny, radiant elements are placed one by one, forming dense rows of color and shape.
As this flow progresses, layers of complementary colors, like calm and internal waves, create smaller and more cohesive structures, as if we are witnessing an ocean of stones, pearls, and colorful reflections.

metadata.name: H II Region #26
metadata.description:
H II region, also known as the ionized region or emission nebula, is a region of space that contains ionized hydrogen gas. These regions are usually located near young and hot stars that produce strong ultraviolet radiation and ionize the hydrogen gas around them. As a result of their light emission at different wavelengths, they are often seen as colorful and beautiful clouds in telescopic images.

metadata.name: Coronado #101
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

Some key commands in live mode:

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000
2 : 6000x7500
3 : 8000x10000
4 : 10000x12500
5 : 12000x15000
6 : 14000x17500
(1-6 work best on Chrome)
(rendering takes longer as resolution increases)
